Evan's boat can move at a speed $u$ in still water. However, today he is in a fast river that flows at a speed $v = 2u$. He starts off a perpendicular distance $r$ from a pier as shown (see figure below). There is a way Evan can power his boat such that he ends up the least distance downstream when he reaches the riverbank. Find this least distance $d$.
\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width = 0.4\linewidth]{boat}
\end{center}

solution:
His net velocity is the sum of the velocities $v$ and $u$, the latter of which Evan can determine the direction. By velocity addition, this looks like this:
\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width = 0.3\linewidth]{vu}
\end{center}
Since we can determine the direction of $u$, the resultant vector $v+u$ can end at any point along the given circle. To minimize the distance we move downstream, we would like $v+u$ to be tangent to the circle like so:
\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width = 0.3\linewidth]{vu2}
\end{center}
And since $v = 2u$, our optimal heading is at an angle of $30^\circ$ to the horizontal. This means the minimum distance we can end up downstream is $$d=\boxed{\sqrt3 r}.$$

problem:
Suppose Evan isn't as bright as he was in Problem Problem 20 and decides to align his rudder directly toward the pier at all times. Assume here that $v=u$. How far does Evan end up downstream when he reaches the riverbank? Also, which of the following graphs is Evan's correct trajectory? (Challenge problem, optional)

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{boat_choices.png}
\end{center}

solution:
The key insight into this problem is that Evan is heading at the same velocity toward the pier and to the right at all times. Observe an arbitrary position here. 
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width = 0.3\linewidth]{boat4} 
\end{center}The two components of velocity are indicated: one caused by the river and one caused by Evan's boat. We can see that the rate at which Evan moves toward the pier is identical to the rate he moves to the right; specifically, $u(1+\cos\theta)$, where $\theta$ is the angle between the vectors. Hence, (and here's the important bit), <strong>given an arbitrary vertical line placed a distance $r$ downstream, Evan will remain equidistant from that vertical line and the pier at all times, because his component of velocity in those directions is equal at all times.</strong> Sound familiar? This is the definition of a parabola, where the pier is the focus and the line is the directrix. By this parabola, the final distance downstream is $d=r/2$ and the correct multiple choice option is <strong>(E)</strong>.

\begin{anum}
        \item When the driving force stops, the acceleration is reduced by $F_f /m = \mu g$, i.e. from the slope at the current point of the graph we need to subtract the slope of it at the origin. A close-up sketch of the graph around the period of gear change is given in the figure below. After the gear change, the new graph follows the ideal graph, but is shifted rightwards by $\tau_2$, this shift is marked also in Fig. Since $2\tau_1 = \tau_2$, the ascending and descending slopes in that close-up sketch must be of equal steepness, i.e. $a = \mu g/2$. So, the gear change takes place at that speed, when the acceleration is twice smaller than at zero-speed. From the graph we can find that $v_0 \approx \boxed{25\, \unit{m/s}}$.
                \begin{center}
            \includegraphics[scale=0.3]{kaldasol}
        \end{center}
        \item The distance difference is the area $S$ between the actual $v(t)$ graph and the ideal one. These graphs coincide for $v < v_0$ and upon achieving the value $v = v_t$. So, the area $S$ is enclosed into the range $v_t > v > v_0$, where the actual graph is, in fact, just the ideal graph, but shifted rightwards by $\tau_2$. This area has a shape of a narrow curved stripe, the horizontal width of which is at every value of $v$ equal to $\tau_2$. One can divide this stripe into tiny horizontal layers of height $\delta$ and width $\tau_2$. If we sum up the surface areas of these layers, we can bring $\tau_2$ before the braces; then, the sum of the layer widths goes into the braces and yields $v_t - v_0$. So, the area $S = \tau_2(v_t-v_0) \approx \boxed{15\, \unit{m}}$.
    \end{anum}

